      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nOxalic acid is one of the strongest organic diacids, with an unusually low pKa₁ (~1.2) due to the electron-withdrawing effect of the adjacent carboxyl group. The relatively large separation between pKa₁ and pKa₂ (~2.6 units) reflects the increased difficulty of removing a second proton from the already negatively charged hydrogen oxalate ion (HL⁻). This strong chelating ability makes oxalate a widely used ligand in coordination chemistry — as evidenced by the 20 different metal–oxalate systems cataloged in SRD-46.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
